{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/kubernetes-local-development-the-correct-way-1bc4b11570d8", "time": 1683008636.645731, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/kubernetes-local-development-the-correct-way-1bc4b11570d8/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "Kubernetes Local Development: The Correct Way | by Dimitris Poulopoulos | Towards Data Science", "h1": "Kubernetes Local Development: The Correct Way", "description": "Kubernetes is an excellent tool for automating deployment, scaling, and management of containerized applications. However, local development on Kubernetes can be a painful process. A typical workflow\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "https://kubernetes.io/", "anchor_text": "Kubernetes", "paragraph_index": 0}, {"url": "https://skaffold.dev/", "anchor_text": "Skaffold", "paragraph_index": 0}, {"url": "https://www.dimpo.me/newsletter?utm_source=article&utm_medium=medium&utm_campaign=skaffold&utm_term=skaffold_kubernetes", "anchor_text": "Learning Rate", "paragraph_index": 2}, {"url": "https://www.dimpo.me/newsletter?utm_source=article&utm_medium=medium&utm_campaign=skaffold&utm_term=skaffold_kubernetes", "anchor_text": "here", "paragraph_index": 2}, {"url": "https://skaffold.dev/docs/install/", "anchor_text": "documentation", "paragraph_index": 4}, {"url": "https://github.com/GoogleContainerTools/skaffold/releases", "anchor_text": "releases page", "paragraph_index": 4}, {"url": "https://golang.org/", "anchor_text": "Go", "paragraph_index": 6}, {"url": "https://skaffold.dev/docs/quickstart/", "anchor_text": "documentation", "paragraph_index": 13}, {"url": "https://github.com/GoogleContainerTools/skaffold/tree/master/examples", "anchor_text": "GitHub", "paragraph_index": 13}, {"url": "https://kustomize.io/", "anchor_text": "Kustomize", "paragraph_index": 13}, {"url": "https://github.com/GoogleContainerTools/jib", "anchor_text": "Jib", "paragraph_index": 13}, {"url": "https://www.dimpo.me/?utm_source=article&utm_medium=medium&utm_campaign=skaffold&utm_term=skaffold_kubernetes", "anchor_text": "Dimitris Poulopoulos", "paragraph_index": 17}, {"url": "https://www.arrikto.com/", "anchor_text": "Arrikto", "paragraph_index": 17}, {"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/medium.com/@dpoulopoulos/follow", "anchor_text": "Medium", "paragraph_index": 18}, {"url": "https://www.linkedin.com/in/dpoulopoulos/", "anchor_text": "LinkedIn", "paragraph_index": 18}, {"url": "https://twitter.com/james2pl", "anchor_text": "@james2pl", "paragraph_index": 18}, {"url": "https://www.dimpo.me/resources/?utm_source=article&utm_medium=medium&utm_campaign=skaffold&utm_term=skaffold_kubernetes", "anchor_text": "resources", "paragraph_index": 18}, {"url": "http://www.dimpo.me", "anchor_text": "www.dimpo.me", "paragraph_index": 20}], "all_paragraphs": ["Kubernetes is an excellent tool for automating deployment, scaling, and management of containerized applications. However, local development on Kubernetes can be a painful process. A typical workflow consists of several distinct steps; check the functionality of the code locally, build and tag a docker image, create a deployment configuration and deploy on Kubernetes. If there is a bug or a need for an upgrade, the developer needs to follow the same procedure from scratch. In their presentation for Next \u201919, Google engineers called this the infinite loop of pain and suffering, So, is there a way to automate the bits that decrease productivity and let the developers focus on the logic of their code? Introducing Skaffold;", "Skaffold is a lightweight, open-source project from Google that facilitates local Kubernetes development. It runs across environments optimizing the development process by offering a rich set of features, essential for native Kubernetes development, including image tagging, resource port-forwarding and logging, file syncing, and much more.", "Learning Rate is a newsletter for those who are curious about the world of AI and MLOps. You\u2019ll hear from me every Friday with updates and thoughts on the latest AI news and articles. Subscribe here!", "Skaffold offers a CLI (Command Line Interface) that enables iterative development, on both local and remote clusters. The tool provides several features that make local development on Kubernetes a joy.", "To install Skaffold follow the instruction provided in the documentation or visit the GitHub releases page to get a specific version. Skaffold provides installation options for Linux, OSX and Microsoft Windows, as well as a docker image. For example, installing Skaffold CLI on Linux is as easy as executing the following command:", "This command installs the latest, stable version of Skaffold. If you want a specific version (e.g., version 1.10.1) just change the command to the following:", "For this section, we will use the simple Go application example provided on the Skaffold GitHub page. Thus, imaging having a simple Go application that prints \u201cHello world!\u201d every second:", "Now we need a Dockerfile to containerize the app and get it ready for Kubernetes deployment:", "Now you might notice something strange about this Dockerfile: it has two FROM lines. This technique is called the builder pattern, and it is used to produce smaller containers. In this case, we use the first container to compile the code, as the golang:1.12.9-alpine3.1 image provides all the necessary tools for the job, while the second image copies over only the compiled binaries and runs the application. Therefore, we can reduce the footprint of our container by orders of magnitude.", "Now that we have the Dockerfile, we need the deployment YAML configuration file:", "This file takes the image getting-started and deploys it in a pod. And this is where the pain stops. We can now run skaffold init and let the tool detect our resources and generate the skaffold YAML configuration file.", "We can now run skaffold run and Skaffold will build our image and deploy it to our local Kubernetes cluster. And if that is not enough try running skaffold dev. This statement will do precisely what the previous command did but also aggregate the logs for the container and print them back at you. Now if you make a change and save the file, watch it as it immediately detects the change and kicks off the build/tag/deploy cycle again.", "By default, Skaffold uses Git tagging for versioning your images, thus if you run docker image ls you will see something like that:", "To dive deeper, check Skaffold\u2019s documentation examples or the tool\u2019s GitHub page. Last but not least, Skaffold plays well with other Kubernetes tools, such as Kustomize and Jib, so, you do not have to change your current workflow.", "In this story, we introduced the infinite loop of pain and suffering every developer enters trying to develop locally on Kubernetes. Then, we introduced Skaffold, an open-source CLI that optimizes the development workflow by offering a rich set of features, essential for native Kubernetes development, including image tagging, resource port-forwarding and logging, file syncing, and much more.", "In a future article, we will make things easier by introducing a sort of graphical user interface for Skaffold, where you can do the same things with a press of a button. Stay tuned!", "EDIT: The new story is now published! Follow the link below\u2026", "My name is Dimitris Poulopoulos, and I\u2019m a machine learning engineer working for Arrikto. I have designed and implemented AI and software solutions for major clients such as the European Commission, Eurostat, IMF, the European Central Bank, OECD, and IKEA.", "If you are interested in reading more posts about Machine Learning, Deep Learning, Data Science, and DataOps, follow me on Medium, LinkedIn, or @james2pl on Twitter. Also, visit the resources page on my website, a place for great books and top-rated courses, to start building your own Data Science curriculum!", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes.", "Machine Learning Engineer. I talk about AI, MLOps, and Python programming. More about me: www.dimpo.me"], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2F1bc4b11570d8&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": "Open in app"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fkubernetes-local-development-the-correct-way-1bc4b11570d8&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign up"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=login&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fkubernetes-local-development-the-correct-way-1bc4b11570d8&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign In"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/?source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": ""}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fnew-story&source=---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------new_post_sidenav-----------", "anchor_text": "Write"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/search?source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": ""}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fkubernetes-local-development-the-correct-way-1bc4b11570d8&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign up"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=login&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fkubernetes-local-development-the-correct-way-1bc4b11570d8&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign In"}, {"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/?source=po